observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a) Require the Municipal Accountant to pass the necessary Adjusting Journal Entry by debiting both RPT and SET receivables by P56,818,442.00 and crediting Deferred Income (RPT and SET) by the same amount to reflect the correct balances of the accounts;
b) Require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, to set-up the RPT and SET receivables every year;
c) Adopt additional measures like deputizing the barangay treasurers, conducting collection caravans and other strategies to improve the collection efficiency of the Municipality of Ternate and to prevent the continued yearly increase/accumulation of uncollected RPT and SET receivables;
d) Direct the Municipal Treasurer to conduct intensive/aggressive tax campaign and information drive in order to encourage/invite more taxpayers to pay their obligations on time and inquire with the Provincial Government of Cavite the details of the status of payment of real property tax penalties thru Dacion En Pago by Puerto Azul;
e) Fill-up vacant positions or augment the number of personnel in the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to help in the Municipality’s collection efforts;
f) Push the execution of New Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) with Puerto Azul Management for the settlement of their RPT and SET dues covering CYs 2013-2018; and
g) Push the execution of a Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) with Caylabne Management (Exchange Properties) for the settlement of their outstanding RPT and SET arrears for CYs 2013 - 2018.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. Direct the Inventory Team to facilitate the conduct of complete physical count of all PPE and prepare and submit the Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain complete and updated Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards for all PPE of the Municipality;
c. Require the General Services Officer to maintain individual Property Cards for all PPE of the Municipality; and
d. Require the Accounting Department and General Services Office to undertake the reconciliation of its records and make the adjustments where needed to arrive at the correct balance of the PPE account.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor ensure propriety in the use of the PCF by:
a. Directing the Accountant and the PCF Custodian to reassess the reasonable amount of PCF to be maintained based on amounts of appropriate petty expenses incurred by the Municipality on a monthly basis;
b. Drafting a policy/guidelines on the use and utilization of the PCF in conformity with COA Circular No. 97-002 and not allowing regular expenditures appropriately paid by checks to be paid out of the PCF for approval by the Sanggunian Bayan;
c. Require the PCF Custodian and the Municipal Accountant to observe the proper replenishment of the PCF; and
d. Direct the PCF Custodian to ensure complete documentation before charges against the fund is allowed in compliance with COA Circular No. 2012-001.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. Formulate a policy/guidelines in the availment and entitlement of motor vehicle rental with the corresponding reasonable rates for control and monitoring purposes;
b. Practice scheduling or timing of transactions by proper communication and coordination of the different departments to maximize the use of motor vehicle rentals;
c. Limit availment of van rentals to necessary and critical transactions only; and
d. Consider prioritizing the purchase of one official vehicle for Municipal Treasurer’s Office and other Departments’ use either brand new or second hand as authorized by NBC Nos. 446 and 446-A.

We recommended that Management:
a) Pass the necessary adjusting journal entry to correct the Land balance as recorded in the books by increasing the account by P82,313.94;
b) Exert extra effort in securing all pertinent documents to facilitate the registration and transfer of the title of the land properties from the previous owners to the Municipality of Ternate;
c) Secure tax assessment from the BIR to know the transfer taxes due and for the Municipality to allot budget to facilitate payment of the same; and
d) Make disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements as regards the status of the titling of the acquired/donated parcels of land.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, the Committee on Finance and the Head of the Department the following:
set a realistic estimated income for local taxes considering that the Municipality did not achieve its target collection for the past two (2) years;
revert the unliquidated accounts payable of P443,000.00 to the appropriated surplus of general fund;
exercise utmost diligence in the disposition of government funds by ensuring that only necessary expenditures are incurred;
continue to limit the expenses to actual income received;
ensure that continuing appropriations and obligations incurred are always supported by funds available for such purpose/s; and
inter-agency payables and other current liabilities that are considered as trust receipts are made available and spent only for the specific purpose for which they were created or received.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor consider the following courses of action:

exercise of utmost diligence in the disposition of government funds;

limit of expenses to actual income received;

continuing appropriations and  obligations incurred are always supported by funds available for such purpose/s; and

inter-agency payables and other current liabilities that are considered as trust receipts are made available and spent only for the specific purpose for which they were created or received.
